{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517109"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:51:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:51:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12758"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12758"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.03,0.02,0.04,0.82]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5205"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96630"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5205"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2023-04-16T21:44:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T14:32:47+10:30","updatedAction":"updated","acceptedAt":"2023-06-01T09:10:43+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-15 16:31:07"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12758"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"6927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79264"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1511"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2934"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"9697"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10981"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43894"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79264"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96630"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic at 35 weeks of gestation with a two-week history of fatigue, nausea and itching, particularly on her palms and soles. Over the last three days, she has also noticed that her urine has become darker and her stools paler in colour. She has a medical history of coeliac disease and takes no regular medications. Her pregnancy has been uncomplicated until now.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 132/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is gravid and non-tender. Laboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum alkaline phosphatase (ALP): 250 IU/L (35-129)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect bilirubin: 35 \u03bcmol/L (0-5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum aspartate aminotransferase (AST): 25 IU/L (0-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum alanine aminotransferase (ALT): 30 IU/L (0-41)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT): 26 IU/L (0-30)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum bile acids: 35 \u03bcmol/L (\u0026lt;19)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Choledocholithiasis","Acute fatty liver of pregnancy","Polymorphic eruption of pregnancy (PUPPP)","HELLP syndrome","Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eintrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy (ICP)\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a condition characterised by impaired bile flow during pregnancy. ICP typically presents with pruritus including the palms and soles without a skin rash, malaise and less commonly pale stools, and dark urine around 28 weeks gestation. It is associated with pre-eclampsia and gestational diabetes. The diagnosis is confirmed by non-fasting serum bile acids above 19 \u03bcmol/L - levels below this with pruritus and no rash is considered gestational pruritus. Liver function tests and bilirubin may be elevated or normal as biochemical changes does not correlate with symptoms, and ALP alone may be elevated with pregnancy. Patients need weekly or fortnightly LFTs and serum bile acid levels until delivery as severe cholestasis (serum bile acids \u0026gt;40\u03bcmol/L) is associated with stillbirth and pre-term birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholedocholithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E, or stones in the bile ducts, occurs in some 15% of cases of gallstones. Whilst these stones can remain symptomless, if they do cause any transient obstruction, the patient is likely to experience colicky abdominal pain and have episodes of pruritus, pale stools, and dark urine. These episodes can occur during pregnancy but the LFT results in cholelithiasis would typically show an increase in serum transaminases and a normal or slightly elevated alkaline phosphatase level. The pattern of itching in the palms and soles in this case, along with raised serum bile acids make choledocholithiasis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute fatty liver of pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but potentially life-threatening condition that occurs in the third trimester of pregnancy. The symptoms of AFLP can include nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, jaundice, coagulopathy and hypoglycaemia. Hypoglycaemia is one of the simple differences between AFLP and its leading differential HELLP syndrome. The LFT results in AFLP would show elevated levels of serum transaminases, bilirubin and ammonia, as well as evidence of liver failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymorphic eruption of pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as Pruritic Urticarial Papules and Plaques of Pregnancy (PUPPP) is an itchy rash that occurs in the final three months of pregnancy, and resolves post-partum. It occurs in ~1/160 pregnancies, and is more common in the first pregnancy. While PUPPP could account for this patient\u0027s pruritis, it would not account for the elevated serum bile acids, nor the absence of rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHELLP syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (Haemolysis, Elevated Liver enzymes and Low Platelets) is a severe manifestation of pre-eclampsia. Typically, transaminases (AST, ALT) are elevated to twice the normal range and patients may complain of headache, vomiting and abdominal pain. HELLP syndrome has a high foetal mortality rate, and can recur in future pregnancies. Hypertension (\u0026gt;140/90) developing after 20 weeks gestation should raise suspicion for pre-eclampsia, and further investigations may reveal HELLP syndrome. As this patient is asymptomatic, not hypertensive and has cholestatic symptoms (e.g. dark urine and pale stools), HELLP syndrome is less likely than ICP, however it is an important differential to consider.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy typically presents with pruritus of the palms and soles without a rash in the third trimester.","Elevated serum bile acids (\u003E19 \u03bcmol/L) confirm the diagnosis of intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy.","Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy requires close monitoring as severe cholestasis (bile acids \u003E40 \u03bcmol/L) is associated with increased risk of stillbirth and preterm birth."],"references":["Hillman SC, Stokes-Lampard H, Kilby MD. Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy. BMJ. 2016 Apr 21;353:i1236. doi: 10.1136/bmj.i1236. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27103313/","Department of Health and Wellbeing, Government of South Australia. Intrahepatic Cholestasis of Pregnancy. 2021 Aug 11. Available from: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/f91fbf004ee530b2a5ebadd150ce4f37/Intrahepatic+cholestasis+of+pregnancy_PPG_v4_0.pdf?MOD=AJPERES","Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Obstetric Cholestasis, green-top guideline no. 43. 2011 Apr. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Obstetric-Cholestasis.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79264"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12758"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79264"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T14:31:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T14:31:52+10:30","number":14,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5205"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96630"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"att